==Notes==
{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}
<ol style="list-style:upper-alpha"><li>{{note label|specialnotes1|A|none}}''Dona'' is a Portuguese and Brazilian honorific added to a name which is rendered in English as [[Dame (title)|Dame]] or [[Lady]], in Italian as ''Donna'' and in Spanish as ''Do<U+00F1>a''. Its male equivalent in Portuguese is [[Dom (title)|Dom]], in English is [[Lord]] and in Spanish or Italian is ''[[Don (honorific)|Don]]''.</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes2|B|none}}The information given is about Emperor Pedro&nbsp;II of Brazil, Maria Am<U+00E9>lia's elder half-brother, but can be applied to her.{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=8}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes3|C|none}}Aureliano Coutinho, the Viscount of Sepetiba, was a politician who headed the "Courtier Faction", a political faction composed of high ranking palace servants and notable politicians. The courtiers exercised a strong influence over Pedro&nbsp;II, who was then no more than an adolescent. Once he matured and gained a full grasp of his capabilities, Maria Am<U+00E9>lia's half-brother decisively engineered an end to the power held by the courtiers. By 1847, the Courtier Faction was no more.{{sfn|Barman|1999|pp=49, 114}} Why he overruled refusals by previous governments to recognize Maria Am<U+00E9>lia as Brazilian princess in order to please the Emperor (e.g. engineered by people such as Sepetiba, whose position relied on staying in Pedro&nbsp;II's good graces) is not known.</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes4|D|none}}Law 184 of 5 July 1841{{sfn|Brazilian Government|1864|pp=8-9}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes5|E|none}}Maximilian died in 1867, six years before Am<U+00E9>lie. Her will disposed that if Maximilian had died without children, her properties would go to her nephew Nicholas, son of [[Maximilian de Beauharnais, 3rd&nbsp;Duke of Leuchtenberg]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=152}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes6|F|none}}First [[Bahia]], then [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro]] and lastly, [[Esp<U+00ED>rito Santo]].{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=123}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes7|G|none}}As can be seeing in the letter dated 8 October 1864 that Maximilian sent to Pedro&nbsp;II when he was already living in Mexico as its emperor: "The recollections that remain in me of the beautiful voyage that I made to Brazil is in my memory and I will never forget; it is with a lively interest that I see the fast development and constant prosperity of Your beautiful Empire. Thanks to the really liberal impulse that Your Majesty can give to its government, Brazil, in a state of peace that gives envy in the New World, works actively for both the public wealth and its general well-being."{{sfn|Almeida|1973|p=123}}</li>
<li>{{note label|specialnotes8|H|none}}The death of Maria Am<U+00E9>lia created the need in Maximilian to relieve his "troubled soul"{{sfn|Longo|2008|p=107}} resulting in his tour of places associated with the princess. The search for links to Maria Am<U+00E9>lia eventually took him to Brazil, where he began to conceive a purpose for his empty life, and this in turn prompted his later acceptance of the Mexican crown with tragic results.{{sfn|Longo|2008|p=107}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=631}} According to historian Pedro Calmon, Maximilian called Pedro II "tutor" and regarded him as an "example". Maximilian told his Brazilian cousin that whatever good he had done for Mexico had been a result of what he learned from Pedro II and Brazil on his 1860 trip.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=755}}</li>
</ol>
{{refend}}

